{"title_page": "Bernard Gallagher", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bernard Gallagher\n| image                   = Bernard_Gallagher.jpg\n| caption                 = \n| birth_name               =\n| birth_date               = {{birth date|df=yes|1929|09|26}}\n| birth_place              = [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date               = {{death date and age|df=yes|2016|11|27|1929|09|26}}\n| death_place              = England\n| restingplace            =\n| othername               =\n| occupation              = Actor\n| yearsactive             =\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Sylvia Vickers |1971|2016|end=his death}}\n| children                = Matthew & Zoe\n| website                 =\n| awards                  =\n}}\n'''Bernard Gallagher''' (26 September 1929 \u2013 27 November 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/bernard-gallagher-1929-2016/|title=Bernard Gallagher 1929 \u2013 2016|website=holby.tv}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/dec/04/bernard-gallagher-obituary|title=Bernard Gallagher obituary|first=Anthony|last=Hayward|date=December 4, 2016|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>) was an English actor known for his stage work, including with the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] and the [[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]]; and his many appearances in television [[soap opera]]s and dramas.<ref name=stage>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/2016/bernard-gallagher/|title=Obituary: Bernard Gallagher &#124; Obituaries|first=Michael|last=Quinn|date=December 15, 2016}}</ref> He was born in [[Bradford]], West Yorkshire.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nGalagher studied English at\u00a0[[Sheffield University]], and following [[National service]] in the [[RAF Educational Service]] (1952-54), made his stage debut in [[Lyme Regis]] in 1956.<ref name=guardian/>Working in regional rep for the next decade, in 1965 he joined London\u2019s [[Royal Court Theatre|Royal Court]] for [[William Gaskill|Bill Gaskill]]\u2019s first season, with roles in (amongst others) the original stage productions of Edward Bond\u2019s ''[[Saved\u00a0(play)|Saved]]'', and\u00a0Joe Orton's ''[[The Ruffian on the Stair]]'' and ''[[The Erpingham Camp]]'' (both 1967).\u00a0<ref name=scotsman>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/bernard-gallagher-1-4317387|title=Bernard Gallagher|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref><ref name=stage/>\n\nLater in 1967, Gallagher began a long association with the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] (1967-1976), when he appeared in [[Clifford Williams (actor)|Clifford Williams]]\u2019 all-male ''[[As You Like It]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/play/3/as-you-like-it/production/a75|title=Production of As You Like It &#124; Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref>\u00a0Other roles included in\u00a0Howard Brenton\u2019s ''[[Weapons of Happiness]]'' and\u00a0Tom Stoppard\u2019s ''[[Jumpers (play)|Jumpers]]''.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nHe also spent two seasons with the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]], and worked for many other theatre companies, such as\u00a0[[Paines Plough]]\u00a0and [[Max Stafford-Clark]]'s\u00a0[[Out of Joint Theatre Company|Out of Joint]].<ref name=guardian/><ref name=stage/>\n\u00a0\n\n[[West End (theatre)|West End]] appearances included [[Michael Frayn]]\u2019s ''Alphabetical Order'' (May Fair Theatre, 1975), [[Willy Russell]]\u2019s ''Breezeblock Park'' ([[Trafalgar Studios|Whitehall Theatre]], 1977) and [[Caryl Churchill]]\u2019s ''Heart\u2019s Desire'' ([[Duke of York's Theatre]], 1997).<ref name=stage/>\n\nGallagher played the lead role of compassionate consultant Ewart Plimmer in the first three years of BBC TV's long-running medical drama series ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2016/12/22/bernard-gallagher-actor-obituary/|title=Bernard Gallagher, actor \u2013 obituary|date=December 22, 2016|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>  In ITV's daytime legal drama series ''[[Crown Court (TV series)|Crown Court]]'', he played [[Barrister]] Jonathan Fry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/589335/credits.html|title=BFI Screenonline: Crown Court (1972-84) Credits|website=www.screenonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nGallagher's numerous other TV credits include that of a Desk Sergeant in the second episode of the hard-hitting 1970s British police drama   ''[[The Sweeney]]'' (episode entitled:  ''Jackpot''), ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]'' and its sister programme ''[[The Royal]]'' (although he played different characters), ''[[Bergerac (TV series)|Bergerac]]'', ''[[Bad Girls (TV series)|Bad Girls]]'', ''[[Wycliffe (TV series)|Wycliffe]]'', ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' and ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=20815|title=Bernard Gallagher|website=www.aveleyman.com}}</ref>  \n\nIn rare comedic roles he played Arthur, the [[Holiday Camp]] manager in ''[[Oh No, It's Selwyn Froggitt!]]'', DS Lang in the \"Photographs\" episode of ''[[Some Mothers Do 'Ave 'Em]]'' and Mr. Glockenspiel in the \"[[List_of_The_Thin_Blue_Line_episodes#Series_2_(1996)|Alternative Culture]]\" episode of ''[[The Thin Blue Line (TV series)|The Thin Blue Line]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishclassiccomedy.co.uk/selwyns-off-broaden-horizons|title=Selwyn's Off To Broaden His Horizon's...|date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b7bcdfb35|title=Some Mothers Do &#039;ave &#039;em[09/12/78] (1978)|website=BFI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/the_thin_blue_line/episodes/2/4/|title=The Thin Blue Line Series 2, Episode 4 - Alternative Culture|first=British Comedy|last=Guide|website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref>\n\nGallagher also portrayed keen gardener Bill Molesley in [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''[[Downton Abbey]]'' (2010-2013); and Enfield in ''[[The Duchess of Duke Street]]'' (series 2, episode 12).<ref name=scotsman/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/1596917c93c947248ac936dd708d1f4b|title=The Duchess of Duke Street|date=November 19, 1977|issue=2819|pages=22|via=BBC Genome}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0302338}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gallagher, Bernard}}\n[[Category:People from Bradford]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bernard Gallagher\n| image                   = Bernard_Gallagher.jpg\n| caption                 = \n| birth_name               =\n| birth_date               = {{birth date|df=yes|1929|09|26}}\n| birth_place              = [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date               = {{death date and age|df=yes|2016|11|27|1929|09|26}}\n| death_place              = England\n| restingplace            =\n| othername               =\n| occupation              = Actor\n| yearsactive             =\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Sylvia Vickers |1971|2016|end=his death}}\n| children                = Matthew & Zoe\n| website                 =\n| awards                  =\n}}\n'''Bernard Gallagher''' (26 September 1929 \u2013 27 November 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/bernard-gallagher-1929-2016/|title=Bernard Gallagher 1929 \u2013 2016|website=holby.tv}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/dec/04/bernard-gallagher-obituary|title=Bernard Gallagher obituary|first=Anthony|last=Hayward|date=December 4, 2016|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>) was an English actor known f